class Solution {
    public boolean search(int[] nums, int target) {
        int lo = 0;
        int hi = nums.length - 1;

        while (lo <= hi) {
            int mid = lo + (hi - lo) / 2;

            // Case 1: Target found
            if (nums[mid] == target) {
                return true;
            }

            /*
             * Case 2: Duplicate ambiguity
             * nums[lo] == nums[mid] == nums[hi]
             * We cannot decide which side is sorted
             * So we shrink the search space
             */
            if (nums[lo] == nums[mid] && nums[mid] == nums[hi]) {
                lo++;
                hi--;
            }

            /*
             * Case 3: Left half is sorted
             */
            else if (nums[lo] <= nums[mid]) {
                // Check if target lies in the left sorted half
                if (nums[lo] <= target && target < nums[mid]) {
                    hi = mid - 1;   // discard right half
                } else {
                    lo = mid + 1;   // discard left half
                }
            }

            /*
             * Case 4: Right half is sorted
             */
            else {
                // Check if target lies in the right sorted half
                if (nums[mid] < target && target <= nums[hi]) {
                    lo = mid + 1;
                } else {
                    hi = mid - 1;
                }
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
}








# Search in Rotated Sorted Array II (LeetCode 81)

## Problem
Given a rotated sorted array that may contain duplicates, determine whether a target value exists.

---

## Approach (Binary Search with Duplicates)

1. Use binary search with `lo`, `mid`, `hi`
2. If `nums[mid] == target` â†’ return true
3. If `nums[lo] == nums[mid] == nums[hi]`
   - We cannot decide which side is sorted
   - Shrink the search space (`lo++`, `hi--`)
4. If left half is sorted:
   - Check whether target lies in left half
5. Else:
   - Right half must be sorted

---

## Edge Cases Covered
- Duplicate values
- Fully rotated array
- Not rotated array
- Target not present
- Single element array

---

## Time Complexity
- Average: O(log n)
- Worst case (due to duplicates): O(n)

---

## Key Learning
Duplicates break the usual binary search guarantees.

